# Efficiency Tips & Workflow

## Code Generation Workflow

### When Creating New Components
1. **Analyze requirements first** - Understand what the component needs to do
2. **Check for existing patterns** - Look at similar components in the codebase
3. **Create component structure** - File, props interface, basic structure
4. **Implement styling** - Use Tailwind classes, reference [code-conventions.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/code-conventions.mdc)
5. **Add interactivity** - State, handlers, Zustand if needed
6. **Write tests** - Create test file alongside component
7. **Format code** - Run `npm run format` before committing

### When Converting Figma Designs
1. **Use Figma analysis rule** - Reference [figma-analysis.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/figma-analysis.mdc)
2. **Break down into components** - Identify reusable pieces
3. **Start with layout** - Structure first, then styling
4. **Use Tailwind utilities** - Don't create custom CSS unless necessary
5. **Test responsive** - Check mobile, tablet, desktop
6. **Verify accessibility** - Keyboard navigation, screen readers

## Keyboard Shortcuts & Tools

### VS Code / Cursor Shortcuts
- `Ctrl/Cmd + .` - Quick fix / suggestions
- `Ctrl/Cmd + Shift + P` - Command palette
- `F2` - Rename symbol (refactor)
- `Ctrl/Cmd + Click` - Go to definition
- `Alt + Click` - Multi-cursor
- `Ctrl/Cmd + D` - Select next occurrence

### Useful Extensions
- ESLint - Code linting
- Prettier - Code formatting (already configured)
- Tailwind CSS IntelliSense - Autocomplete for Tailwind
- TypeScript Importer - Auto-import types
- Error Lens - Inline error display

## Code Review Checklist

Before submitting code:
- [ ] TypeScript types are correct (no `any` types)
- [ ] Code formatted with Prettier
- [ ] No console.logs or debug code
- [ ] Tests written and passing
- [ ] Component is accessible
- [ ] Responsive design implemented
- [ ] No unused imports or variables
- [ ] Follows project file structure

## Common Patterns to Reuse

### Button Component
```tsx
<button
  onClick={handleClick}
  className="px-4 py-2 rounded-lg font-semibold transition-colors bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700 text-white"
>
  {label}
</button>
```

### Input Component
```tsx
<input
  type="text"
  value={value}
  onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)}
  className="w-full px-3 py-2 border border-gray-300 rounded-lg focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-blue-500"
/>
```

### Loading Spinner
```tsx
<div className="flex items-center justify-center p-8">
  <div className="animate-spin rounded-full h-8 w-8 border-b-2 border-blue-600"></div>
</div>
```

## Debugging Tips

1. **Use React DevTools** - Inspect component state and props
2. **Use TypeScript** - Catch errors at compile time
3. **Console debugging** - Use `console.log` strategically (remove before commit)
4. **Breakpoints** - Use browser DevTools for runtime debugging
5. **Test in isolation** - Test components separately before integration

## Performance Optimization

1. **Memoization** - Use `React.memo`, `useMemo`, `useCallback` when needed
2. **Code splitting** - Lazy load routes and heavy components
3. **Image optimization** - Use appropriate image formats and sizes
4. **Bundle analysis** - Check bundle size with `npm run build` and analyze

## Git Workflow

1. **Small commits** - One feature/fix per commit
2. **Descriptive messages** - "Add user profile component" not "Update code"
3. **Branch naming** - `feature/component-name`, `fix/bug-description`
4. **Format before commit** - Run `npm run format` or use pre-commit hook

## Asking for Help

When stuck, provide:
1. What you're trying to achieve
2. What you've tried
3. Error messages (if any)
4. Relevant code snippets
5. Expected vs actual behavior
